  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "17–25. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Directions as to the quality of offerings",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Directions as to the quality of offerings",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "p",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This passage retains clear signs of a remarkably composite character. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:17-18 a",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 22:17-18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " a",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " indicate (‘unto Aaron, and to his sons,’ ‘unto all etc.’) that what follows is a blending of directions referring to priests and to the people. But further, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:21",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 22:21",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " presents what is virtually a repetition of the directions in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:18-20",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 22:18-20",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", while the differences in phraseology between the two point to diversity of origin. We notice further that the classes of offerings dealt with differ, viz. Burnt-Offerings and Peace-Offerings respectively, while each of these have the same sub-divisions, i.e. Vows and Freewill-Offerings, the former passage making no reference to other classes of Burnt-Offerings, such as the Sin-Offerings and Guilt-Offerings (4, 5), and the latter ignoring the third species, viz. Thank-Offering (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:29",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 22:29",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), included (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") under the genus Peace-Offering. Moreover, within the parallelism (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:18-20",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 22:18-20",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as compared with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:21",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 22:21",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") there are marked differences in phraseology (e.g. ‘of the beeves, of the sheep, or of the goats,’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:19",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 22:19",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ‘of the herd or of the flock,’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:21",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 22:21",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). For other differences see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Oxf. Hex.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which further points out the frequent changes in number and person in 18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "–20 as indicating successive editorial revisions.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 17-25.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Just as the priests who offer to the Lord are to be ceremonially and morally holy, so the animals offered to him are to be physically perfect, in order ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(1)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to be types of a future perfect Victim, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to symbolize the \"perfect heart\"which God requires to be given to him, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(3)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to teach the duty of offering to him of our best. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Whatsoever hath a blemish,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "shall ye not offer.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The list of blemishes and malformations which exclude from the altar is given; they are such as deform the animal, and make it less valuable: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "blind, or broken, or maimed, or having a wen, or scurvy, or scabbed, ye shall not offer these unto the Lord,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " nor any animal that is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "bruised, or crushed, or broken, or cut",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, castrated in any manner. The clause following the mention of castration - neither shall ye make any offering thereof in your land - literally translated, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "neither shall ye make in your land",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", probably forbids castration altogether, not merely the offering of castrated animals in sacrifice. The expression, Ye shall offer at your own will, should be understood, as before, for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "your acceptance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see note on Leviticus 2:1). Only one exception is made as to blemished offerings: an animal ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "that hath any thing superfluous or lacking in his parts",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " may be offered for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "a freewill offering",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but not ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "for a vow",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (for the distinction of these offerings, see note on chapter Leviticus 2:1). These rules as to unblemished victims are to apply to the offerings of strangers as well as of Israelites. Leviticus 22:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Acceptable Sacrifices. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:18-20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Every sacrifice offered to the Lord by an Israelite or foreigner, in consequence of a vow or as a freewill-offering (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), was to be faultless and male, \"for good pleasure to the offerer\" (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), i.e., to secure for him the good pleasure of God. An animal with a fault would not be acceptable. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]